abstract: Investors reckon passage of the budget blueprint improves Republicans’ chances of getting some kind of tax overhaul through Congress.
snippet: Investors reckon passage of the budget blueprint improves Republicans’ chances of getting some kind of tax overhaul through Congress.
lead_paragraph: Good Friday morning from Andrew Ross Sorkin in New York and Michael J. de la Merced and Amie Tsang in London. We’re thinking about the implications of Lyft’s $1 billion investment from Alphabet and how that changes its battle with Uber — and all the companies like Apple that have invested in one or the other. More on all those frenemies in a moment.

abstract: The annual charity event might have lacked the elegance — and bite — of last year’s, but there was no shortage of zingers.
snippet: The annual charity event might have lacked the elegance — and bite — of last year’s, but there was no shortage of zingers.
lead_paragraph: When Paul D. Ryan, the House speaker, rose to deliver the keynote address at the Al Smith charity dinner on Thursday night, he immediately let it be known that he wouldn’t shy away from jokes about a president who doesn’t react well to jokes.

abstract: Go to Yankee Stadium? Buy from Amazon or Starbucks? Mayor Bill de Blasio just can’t do it, even when his job would seem to call for such gestures.
snippet: Go to Yankee Stadium? Buy from Amazon or Starbucks? Mayor Bill de Blasio just can’t do it, even when his job would seem to call for such gestures.
lead_paragraph: Hours after New York City released its bid for Amazon’s second headquarters, Mayor Bill de Blasio conveyed an entirely different message to a Brooklyn audience on Wednesday night: The behemoth online retailer is bad for small businesses. Shop local, like he does.

abstract: When the American Express C.E.O. steps down in February, there may be just three black men running Fortune 500 companies.
snippet: When the American Express C.E.O. steps down in February, there may be just three black men running Fortune 500 companies.
lead_paragraph: Good Thursday morning from Andrew Ross Sorkin in New York and Michael J. de la Merced and Amie Tsang in London. We’re thinking about the implications of the decision by Ken Chenault, one of the financial world’s biggest names, to retire as C.E.O. of American Express next year. More on that in a moment.

abstract: The school has not only recovered from financial woes, but is pivoting from a place that primarily provides arts education to a full-fledged performing arts center.
snippet: The school has not only recovered from financial woes, but is pivoting from a place that primarily provides arts education to a full-fledged performing arts center.
lead_paragraph: After hundreds of children had finished their dance, piano and voice lessons one recent afternoon, the halls of the Harlem School of the Arts were quiet. Construction workers had also departed, leaving their tools behind.

abstract: The mayoral candidate faces long odds to unseat the Democrat incumbent, Mayor Bill de Blasio.
snippet: The mayoral candidate faces long odds to unseat the Democrat incumbent, Mayor Bill de Blasio.
lead_paragraph: During nearly seven years as a Republican in the New York State Assembly, Nicole Malliotakis earned a reputation for embracing unpopular stances in the Democrat-controlled chamber, opposing minimum wage increases, paid family leave, gay marriage and public financing of elections.

abstract: International delegates will gather next month to discuss implementing the Paris agreement, and American negotiators will be there even though the United States has said it will quit the pact.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When Trump administration officials travel to Germany next month for United Nations climate change discussions, they will face a fundamental contradiction: how to negotiate the terms of a deal they say they’re walking away from.
